          <msContents>
            <summary>Manuscript is used for meditation, contemplation, and recitation and its text, a praise of the Hindu deity Śiva, is the product of a hallucinogenic experience. The poet, an Advaita (non-dualism) Vedānta philosopher writing from a Śaiva perspective, consumed a drug which is derived from the datura plant, known to be especially sacred to Śiva.</summary>
            <textLang mainLang="san">In Sanskrit</textLang>
            <msItem>
              <title>Ātmārpaṇastuti</title>
              <title type="vernacular">आत्मार्पणस्तुति</title>
              <author>
                <persName type="authority">Appayya Dīkṣita</persName>
              </author>
              <colophon>Colophon: iti śrīmadadvaitācāryaśrīmadappaiyyadīkṣitaviracitā ātmārpaṇasstutiḥ saṃpūrṇatāmagamat // śrīśivaśivā 'arpaṇam astu // mi - mārga - śu - 8 śanau saṃ[vat] - 1909 (f. 9v).</colophon>
            </msItem>
